<div class="display-inline-block"><button type="button" class="cursor-pointer text-no-underline bg-transparent border-0 padding-0 text-left margin-0 text-normal text-primary" aria-controls="journal_context_menu">Ophthalmology</button></div>. Author manuscript; available in PMC: 2023 Oct 1.</div>
<div>
<em>Published in final edited form as: </em>Ophthalmology. 2022 Sep 1;129(10):e146–e149. doi: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ophtha.2022.06.035" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">10.1016/j.ophtha.2022.06.035</a>
</div>
<nav id="journal_context_menu" hidden="hidden"><ul class="menu-list font-family-ui" role="menu">
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/?term="Ophthalmology"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PMC</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Ophthalmology"[jour]' lang="en" class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PubMed</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term="Ophthalmology"[Title%20Abbreviation]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">View in NLM Catalog</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="Ophthalmology"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>Data Sources for Evaluating Health Disparities in Ophthalmology: Where We Are and Where We Need to Go</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MSc</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>1</sup>Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>2</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Baxter%20SL"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Sally L Baxter</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>1,</sup><sup>2</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Nwanyanwu%20K"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">Kristen Nwanyanwu</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Kristen Nwanyanwu</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MBA. MHS</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Science, Yale University</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Nwanyanwu%20K"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Kristen Nwanyanwu</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>3</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Legault%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Gary Legault</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Gary Legault</span>, <span class="degrees">MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>4</sup>Department of Ophthalmology, Brooke Army Medical Center</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Legault%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Gary Legault</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>4</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Lee%20AY"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id4"><span class="name western">Aaron Y Lee</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id4">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Aaron Y Lee</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MSCI</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>5</sup>Department of Ophthalmology, University of Washington</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Lee%20AY"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Aaron Y Lee</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>5</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>1</sup>Viterbi Family Department of Ophthalmology and Shiley Eye Institute, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>2</sup>Health Department of Biomedical Informatics, University of California San Diego, La Jolla, CA</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>3</sup>Department of Ophthalmology and Visual Science, Yale University</div>
<div id="A4">
<sup>4</sup>Department of Ophthalmology, Brooke Army Medical Center</div>
<div id="A5">
<sup>5</sup>Department of Ophthalmology, University of Washington</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="CR1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline"><strong>Corresponding Author:</strong> Aaron Y. Lee, MD, MSCI, University of Washington, 325 Ninth Ave, Box 359608, Seattle, WA 98104-2499, <span>leeay@uw.edu</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2022 Oct.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC9509471  NIHMSID: NIHMS1831457  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36058733/" class="usa-link">36058733</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.ophtha.2022.06.035" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Ophthalmology</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="ABS1"><h2>Precis</h2>
<p id="P1">Existing data sources for health equity research in ophthalmology lack key information for evaluating the true landscape of eye care disparities in the United States.</p></section><section id="S1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Introduction</h2>
<p id="P2">Data provides an opportunity to discover disparities and inequities that may otherwise be unrecognized. Within the American Academy of Ophthalmology (AAO) Task Force on Disparities in Eye Care, the Leveraging Data Sub-task Force was charged with identifying data sources to study health disparities in eye care and to leverage data to advance health equity. We evaluated large data sources to determine their strengths, deficiencies, and relative accessibility in relation to the likelihood of identifying eye care disparities. In this paper, we highlight the current challenges with these data sources and review key recommendations for improving future sources for studying health disparities in eye care.</p></section><section id="S2"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Existing Data Sources</h2>
<p id="P3">Ophthalmology-specific datasets that contain electronic health record (EHR) data include the AAO IRIS<sup>®</sup> Registry (Intelligent Research in Sight),<sup><a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1">1</a>,<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2">2</a></sup> a Veterans Affairs dataset,<sup><a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3">3</a>–<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5">5</a></sup> and the Sight Outcomes Research Collaborative (SOURCE).<sup><a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6">6</a>,<a href="#R7" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R7">7</a></sup> These datasets provide deidentified clinical care data elements that include self-reported race and ethnicity. Less specific to ophthalmology are large administrative claims datasets such as the All-Payers Claim Databases<sup><a href="#R8" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R8">8</a>,<a href="#R9" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R9">9</a></sup> or the Centers for Medicare &amp; Medicaid Services Medicare Claims,<sup><a href="#R10" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R10">10</a>,<a href="#R11" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R11">11</a></sup> which can provide social information such as income and disability status. Another recommended source is the Vision and Eye Health Surveillance System (VEHSS), which was created by the Centers for Disease Control, and the nonpartisan and objective research organization, NORC, at the University of Chicago.<sup><a href="#R12" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R12">12</a></sup> The VEHSS provides data on national trends and discrepancies on visual impairment and, most importantly, includes individuals who may not be able to access eye care services. Finally, studies such as the National Institutes of Health (NIH) All of Us Research Program<sup><a href="#R13" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R13">13</a></sup> and Healthy People 2030<sup><a href="#R14" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R14">14</a></sup> may provide valuable information to help characterize social determinants.</p></section><section id="S3"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Current Data Gaps</h2>
<p id="P4">Although these databases provide a unique and statistically powerful opportunity to study health care disparities, they also have significant limitations. Medical databases derived from EHRs or insurance claims do not contain information on individuals who lack access to health care resources, where the true disparities likely exist. Furthermore, these databases lack important information for examining social determinants of health. For example, even basic demographic factors such as race, ethnicity, and gender often have limited flexibility in values and in scope. In addition, more granular data regarding other aspects of social determinants (such as housing, transportation, food security, education level, and income) are inconsistently included. At the same time, the databases that do contain such information rarely, if ever, include relevant ophthalmic data such as visual acuity or ophthalmic imaging, which are important for determining outcomes.</p></section><section id="S4"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">How to Improve Data Collection</h2>
<section id="S5"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">(1). Collect more data from existing sources</h3>
<p id="P5">Two methods to improve the current datasets are to increase the provision of data by ophthalmologists and to expand the scope of collected information. Ophthalmologists should be encouraged to participate in and contribute data to ophthalmology-specific databases (e.g., IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry, SOURCE) as well as in broader research initiatives outside of ophthalmology (e.g., All of Us). The IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry has effectively encouraged participation by allowing ophthalmologists to leverage the registry to assist with Medicare reporting requirements,<sup><a href="#R15" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R15">15</a></sup> which has contributed to the IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry becoming the world’s largest specialty clinical data registry.<sup><a href="#R16" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R16">16</a></sup> The AAO and IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry should continue to encourage ophthalmologists’ participation through awareness campaigns and optimization of tools that enable individual practices and physicians to utilize the database for quality improvement efforts and ease of reporting.</p>
<p id="P6">The broader data collection initiatives, such as All of Us, aim to establish broad, diverse enrollment<sup><a href="#R17" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R17">17</a></sup> and include data elements specifically related to social determinants that are more detailed than those in ophthalmology-specific databases. Increasing awareness of these programs within the ophthalmology community will be important to encourage enrollment of patients with eye conditions to ensure that these patients are represented in these national cohort studies.</p>
<p id="P7">In addition, expansion of the data elements, especially those pertaining to social determinants of health, should be a priority. For example, IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry currently does not include variables related to the patient’s language, access to a primary care provider, primary or current insurance carrier (although multiple insurers can be listed), substance use (except for tobacco), or any data elements directly reflecting socioeconomic status. Although some associations may be inferred from existing data elements such as zip code, future iterations of the registry may consider adding more granular, patient-specific data elements to allow more detailed analyses of social determinants in relation to ophthalmology outcomes.</p></section><section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">(2). Collect data using standardized tools and definitions</h3>
<p id="P8">The lack of common data standards or models is a substantial barrier to achieving generalizable results that can be compared across different institutions, locations, or data sources. For example, even the possible values for race and ethnicity vary among data sources, making comparisons or harmonization of health disparities difficult. Several common data models have been developed for EHR data, including the Informatics for Integrating Biology &amp; the Bedside model<sup><a href="#R18" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R18">18</a></sup> or the Observational Medical Outcomes Partnership (OMOP) Common Data Model.<sup><a href="#R19" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R19">19</a></sup></p>
<p id="P9">The OMOP model underlies many general medical databases such as All of Us and the Veterans Affairs data repository. However, ophthalmic databases have generally not adopted these common data models, likely because they do not currently meet the needs of ophthalmology and the vision research community. Our specialty would benefit from reevaluating OMOP and engaging with its governing body (Observational Health Data Sciences and Informatics) to evaluate how ophthalmology-related data elements could be effectively incorporated. Otherwise, opportunities will be missed for leveraging the massive datasets that are currently mapped to OMOP.</p>
<p id="P10">Further, to improve data sources and analyses that include self-reported questionnaires on social determinants, researchers should be encouraged to use validated, standardized survey instruments whenever possible. Doing so will further promote standardization and facilitate cross-comparisons.</p></section><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">(3). Democratize access to datasets</h3>
<p id="P11">Well-constructed datasets that contain variables designed to uncover health care disparities are critically important; another essential, but often-overlooked component, is equity in access to these datasets. Ideally, there would be complete democratization of datasets, whereby the data originate directly from the participants, and citizen-scientists as well as clinical researchers would enjoy equal access the data. In practice, however, often there are barriers to broad data access, whether due to concerns about data privacy or to institutional or other impediments.</p>
<p id="P12">Recently, as part of this initiative, we have begun to explore the use of simplified research scripts to accelerate and prioritize the study of health care disparities through the AAO IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry. In this framework, researchers from outside institutions who are studying health care disparities will develop and submit their unique research scripts to run against the IRIS<sup><em>®</em></sup> Registry database and thus obtain answers to research questions without directly accessing the underlying data. This approach enables analyses from diverse research teams and illustrates a strategy for functionally providing data access even when direct access is not feasible.</p></section><section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">(4). Ensure trust in data collection</h3>
<p id="P13">When patients are reluctant to participate in studies that collect and maintain large data sources, their trepidation is often grounded in a legacy of inappropriate research-participant relationships.<sup><a href="#R20" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R20">20</a></sup> Now, however, many safety measures are available to ensure privacy and appropriate treatment of participant information.<sup><a href="#R21" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R21">21</a></sup> It is the responsibility of researchers to address those fears in the light of past wrongs and ongoing systemic racism and societal inequity. As has been demonstrated in the COVID-19 vaccine campaign,<sup><a href="#R22" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R22">22</a></sup> health care hesitancy is multifactorial, and research relationships are no different.<sup><a href="#R23" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R23">23</a></sup> Once we acknowledge the wrongdoings of the past, the burden of proof is on researchers to ethically design studies with participants. We recommend that ophthalmologists adopt a community-engaged<sup><a href="#R24" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R24">24</a></sup> framework that involves communities in research design and implementation. Community partnership is essential to achieving a shared vision of ethically necessary data elements and patient-centered research questions.</p></section><section id="S9"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">(5). Create and fund new datasets</h3>
<p id="P14">Given that existing data sources have some limitations that may not be easily overcome, another solution is to develop new data sources altogether. Ideally, these data sources would incorporate granular data encompassing both social determinants of health and ophthalmic outcomes and, additionally, would include individuals who may not already have access to health care (and thus would not be represented in large claims databases or EHR-derived data sources).</p>
<p id="P15">The NIH has announced several large initiatives to focus on diverse datasets and researchers, most notably with the recent Bridge to Artificial Intelligence<sup><a href="#R25" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R25">25</a></sup> and the Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning Consortium to Advance Health Equity and Researcher Diversity<sup><a href="#R26" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R26">26</a></sup> funding mechanisms. These initiatives aim to stimulate generation of novel datasets that can address health disparities and to involve diverse multidisciplinary research teams. These efforts also align with National Academy of Medicine’s 2016 report on eye health, which emphasizes the need to establish a series of longitudinal community-based studies to collect long-term data on temporal trends in vision loss, access to care, changes in social determinants of health in various communities, and other variables.<sup><a href="#R27" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R27">27</a></sup> The creation of community-based studies should follow standardized definitions and track outcomes to help identify eye care disparities.</p>
<p id="P16">Funding agencies should continue to prioritize the investigation of health disparities by expanding existing data sources, facilitating the development of novel data sources that will advance this area of research, and supporting researchers from diverse backgrounds, particularly those who have been traditionally underrepresented in biomedical and clinical research.</p></section></section><section id="S10"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Conclusion</h2>
<p id="P17">The key to understanding health care disparities is in the construction of relevant datasets through which social determinants of health can be quantified and measured. In addition, future interventions to improve health care disparities will require establishing baselines prior to the intervention as well as outcome measures to assess the impact on society. It is our hope that these recommendations provide a framework for understanding how data could be leveraged in the future to close the gap in health care disparities and elevate the standard of care.</p></section><section id="S11" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">ACKNOWLEDGMENTS</h2>
<p id="P18">The authors wish to thank the entire sub-task force committee: David Friedman, MD, MPH, PhD, Charles Wright, PhD, James Gao, PhD, and Debra Rosencrance.</p>
